  "article1Title": "What is a period?",
  "article1Summary": "Understand what's happening in your body",
  "article1Content": "A period is when blood comes out of your vagina for a few days each month. It's totally normal and happens to almost every girl and woman.\n\nYour body has a uterus, which is like a small pocket inside your belly. Every month, the uterus prepares a soft lining in case a baby starts to grow. When no baby grows, the lining isn't needed, so your body releases it — that's your period.\n\nMost periods last 3 to 7 days. The blood comes out slowly, not all at once. You can't feel it leaving your body, just like you can't feel when you're sweating.\n\nIt's completely normal to feel a mix of emotions about getting your first period: excitement, confusion, even a bit of worry. All of these feelings are valid. You're not alone — every woman in the world has been through this.",
  "article2Title": "When will my first period come?",
  "article2Summary": "Signs to watch for",
  "article2Content": "Most girls get their first period between 10 and 15 years old. But every body is different. Some girls start at 9, others at 16 — both are perfectly normal.\n\nSome signs that your first period might be coming soon:\n\n• You've started developing breasts (about 2 years before usually)\n• You've noticed hair growing under your arms or in your pubic area\n• You've seen a clear or white liquid in your underwear (this is called discharge — it's normal and healthy)\n• You feel a little tired or moody sometimes\n\nDon't worry if you don't see all these signs. Your body has its own timing. The best thing you can do is to be ready: keep a pad or panty liner in your school bag, just in case.",
  "article3Title": "How to use a pad",
  "article3Summary": "Step by step",
  "article3Content": "Pads are the easiest option for your first period. Here's how to use one:\n\n1. Wash your hands.\n\n2. Unwrap the pad from its packaging. You'll see a sticky side covered by paper.\n\n3. Peel off the paper to expose the sticky side.\n\n4. Stick the pad to the inside of your underwear, with the sticky side down. Center it so it covers from front to back.\n\n5. If the pad has 'wings' (little flaps on the sides), fold them around the underwear and stick them underneath.\n\n6. Pull your underwear up. The pad should feel comfortable and stay in place.\n\n7. Change your pad every 4 to 6 hours, or sooner if it feels full. Wrap the used pad in toilet paper and put it in the trash (never flush it).\n\nThat's it! With practice, it becomes really easy.",
  "article4Title": "What to keep in your bag",
  "article4Summary": "Be prepared at school or outside",
  "article4Content": "Being prepared makes everything easier. Keep these items in a small pouch in your school bag:\n\n• 2 or 3 pads (regular size is fine)\n• A pair of clean underwear (just in case)\n• A small pack of tissues\n• A small plastic bag (to wrap a used pad if there's no trash can nearby)\n\nOptional but useful:\n• A small chocolate or snack (periods can make you hungry)\n• A pain reliever if you sometimes get cramps (ask your parent first)\n\nMost schools have nurses or female teachers who can help you if you're caught off guard. Don't be afraid to ask — they've helped many girls before you.",
  "article5Title": "Dealing with cramps",
  "article5Summary": "What to do when it hurts",
  "article5Content": "Some periods come with cramps — a dull pain in your lower belly or back. It's caused by your uterus gently squeezing to release its lining. Cramps can be mild or stronger, and they usually last 1 to 2 days.\n\nThings that can help:\n\n• A warm pad or hot water bottle on your belly\n• A warm bath or shower\n• Drinking warm water or herbal tea\n• Gentle stretching or a short walk\n• Resting if you're really tired\n• Eating regularly — skipping meals can make cramps worse\n\nIf your cramps are very strong (you can't go to school or you're in tears), tell a parent or a doctor. There are safe medicines and treatments that can really help.\n\nThis pain is real and valid — never let anyone tell you it's 'just in your head'.",
  "article6Title": "When to talk to a doctor",
  "article6Summary": "Signs that need attention",
  "article6Content": "Most period changes are normal, but sometimes you should talk to an adult or a doctor. Tell a trusted adult if:\n\n• You're 16 or older and you haven't had your first period yet\n• Your period is very heavy (you soak a pad in less than 1 hour)\n• Your period lasts more than 7 days\n• You have very strong pain that doesn't go away with rest or warmth\n• You feel dizzy or very weak during your period\n• You get a period more than once a month, or you skip several months in a row (after the first 2 years)\n• You have a fever during your period\n\nDoctors and nurses talk about periods every day. They won't judge you, and they're there to help. You can always ask to see a female doctor if you feel more comfortable."
